Let $y = f(x)$. Then the problem becomes

\begin{align*}\frac{dy}{dx} = xy\end{align*}

Separating and solving yields

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dx} &= xy \\
\frac{dy}{y} &= xdx \\
\int\frac{dy}{y} &= \int xdx \\
\ln|y| &= \frac{x^{2}}{2} + C \end{align*}

When $x=0$ we know that $y=e$ and plugging this information in yields

\begin{align*}1 = \ln(e) = \ln|e| = \frac{(0)^{2}}{2} + C = C\end{align*}

Continuing to simplify yields

\begin{align*}
\ln|y| &= \frac{x^{2}}{2} + C \\
\ln|y| &= \frac{x^{2}}{2} + 1 \\
|y| &= e^{x^{2}/2 + 1} \\
y &= \pm e^{x^{2}/2 + 1} \end{align*}

Since \emph{y} is a positive function, we know that the final answer is

\begin{align*}y = e^{x^{2}/2 + 1}\end{align*}

as required.
